00:00:37.820 --> 00:00:40.040
of what your grades
are, and what you're

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:43.410
likely to do if you keep on
giving the same performance

00:00:43.410 --> 00:00:46.400
you've had so far.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:49.740
Now, today, we're going to
switch gears again and cover

00:00:49.740 --> 00:00:51.577
the last topic for the course.

00:00:51.577 --> 00:00:53.160
For the remainder
of the course, we're

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:55.800
going to talk about probability.

00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:58.880
It's one of the most
important subjects in all

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:00.540
of math or computer science.

00:01:00.540 --> 00:01:03.020
In fact, I was at a frat
last night for dinner,

00:01:03.020 --> 00:01:05.550
and they asked me what my
favorite algorithm was.

00:01:05.550 --> 00:01:08.340
And I couldn't really think
about my favorite algorithm

00:01:08.340 --> 00:01:11.370
was, but in terms of one of the
most important subjects for you

00:01:11.370 --> 00:01:15.730
to know about, after induction,
it's probably probability.

00:01:15.730 --> 00:01:18.850
It's really important across
math and computer science.

00:01:18.850 --> 00:01:21.812
Most of the upper level courses
you take in computer science

00:01:21.812 --> 00:01:23.020
are going to use probability.

00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:25.660
They're going to expect
you to know the basics.

00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:29.110
For example, when you're
designing algorithms in 006

00:01:29.110 --> 00:01:33.360
or 6046, you're going to
be designing in some cases

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:36.990
probabilistic algorithms--
algorithms that flip coins

00:01:36.990 --> 00:01:39.910
or generate random
numbers to get the result.

00:01:39.910 --> 00:01:43.410
And by using randomness,
they run faster.

00:01:43.410 --> 00:01:45.800
If you're doing software
engineering later,

00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:47.300
you're going to use
probability when

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:51.950
you analyze system performance
or build hash tables.

00:01:51.950 --> 00:01:54.190
Probability is used
in information theory,

00:01:54.190 --> 00:01:57.590
in coding theory,
in cryptography.

00:01:57.590 --> 00:02:01.150
In fact, our nation's
codes, their security

00:02:01.150 --> 00:02:04.150
depends on
probabilistic analysis.

00:02:04.150 --> 00:02:06.580
Because the bad guys
are using probabilistic

00:02:06.580 --> 00:02:09.199
algorithms to break
the crypto-system.

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:12.920
And we'll give an example of
that in another week or so.

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:14.820
Probability is
obviously important

00:02:14.820 --> 00:02:18.240
if you're doing game theory
or if you like to gamble,

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:19.480
really critical in gambling.

00:02:19.480 --> 00:02:22.100
In fact, we're going to analyze
a lot of different gambling

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:23.350
games over the next few weeks.

00:02:23.350 --> 00:02:25.710
And for fun, we'll
play some in class.

00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:28.170
In fact, we'll play
one later today.

00:02:28.170 --> 00:02:32.010
And it's amazing how often
the intuition is wrong.

00:02:32.010 --> 00:02:33.440
You think the
answer goes one way,

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:36.000
and then it's
actually the other.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.160
Probability is important in
the study of fault tolerance.

00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:41.090
For example, how
do you figure out

00:02:41.090 --> 00:02:43.730
the probability there's going
to be some critical failure that

00:02:43.730 --> 00:02:46.120
causes the space
shuttle to crash?

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:48.990
Or a critical failure that
causes a nuclear plant

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:50.350
to meltdown?

00:02:50.350 --> 00:02:52.250
That's done through
probabilistic analysis.

00:02:52.250 --> 00:02:54.780
And we'll do some
examples of that.

00:02:54.780 --> 00:02:57.370
Probability comes
up in everyday life.

00:02:57.370 --> 00:02:59.112
We just had an election.

00:02:59.112 --> 00:03:00.570
And running up to
the election, you

00:03:00.570 --> 00:03:03.780
get all these polls that
say that's so-and-so

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:08.060
is ahead of so-and-so by three
points with a margin of error

00:03:08.060 --> 00:03:09.780
of five points.

00:03:09.780 --> 00:03:12.650
So it's a statistical dead
heat, is what they say.

00:03:12.650 --> 00:03:14.930
Well, what the heck
does that mean?

00:03:14.930 --> 00:03:16.990
In fact, usually they've
got it screwed up.

00:03:16.990 --> 00:03:19.156
And we're going to spend
the recitation where you're

00:03:19.156 --> 00:03:22.880
going to do a margin of
error analysis for a poll,

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:25.500
and see how many people
do you need to poll to get

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:28.490
a pretty accurate result?

00:03:28.490 --> 00:03:31.390
Comes up in the medical studies.

00:03:31.390 --> 00:03:34.400
Does cholesterol
cause heart disease?

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:37.090
Does smoking cause lung cancer?

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:39.410
How effective is a certain drug?

00:03:39.410 --> 00:03:43.780
Say you get tested for a disease
and it comes back positive.

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:45.950
Well, there's false positives
and false negatives.

00:03:45.950 --> 00:03:48.970
What are the chances you
really have the disease?

00:03:48.970 --> 00:03:51.942
So the list goes on and on.

00:03:51.942 --> 00:03:53.900
In fact, we're going to
see all these examples.

00:03:53.900 --> 00:03:55.910
We've got eight lectures
and eight recitations.

00:03:55.910 --> 00:03:58.020
And there's just no end
of interesting examples

00:03:58.020 --> 00:04:00.770
where probability
comes into play.

00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:04.920
The bad news is,
probability is probably

00:04:04.920 --> 00:04:09.400
the most misunderstood
subject in all of mathematics

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:11.370
and the sciences.

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:15.750
In fact, Mark Twain
once said, there's

00:04:15.750 --> 00:04:23.300
three kinds of lies-- lies,
damned lies, and statistics,

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:25.210
meaning probability.

00:04:25.210 --> 00:04:29.890
Because it's so easy
to lie with statistics.

00:04:29.890 --> 00:04:33.750
And we're going to see lots
and lots of examples of that.

00:04:33.750 --> 00:04:36.790
In fact, newspaper
articles, you know,

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:40.000
have all sorts of things that
are just horribly fallacious

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:41.032
based on statistics.

00:04:41.032 --> 00:04:41.990
And we'll see examples.

00:04:41.990 --> 00:04:46.690
In fact, we're going to even
debunk a very famous article--

00:04:46.690 --> 00:04:48.920
published research paper--
by some famous computer

00:04:48.920 --> 00:04:50.720
scientists at Berkeley.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:53.610
Where they got to a conclusion
using a very standard method

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:56.650
you see all the time--
completely fallacious.

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:58.120
And we'll see that.

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:00.280
So you can think of that
as, I'm going to teach you

00:05:00.280 --> 00:05:03.080
how to lie with statistics.

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:08.380
Even better, how not to be taken
in by incorrect arguments using

00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:10.860
probability theory.

00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:15.390
Now, at MIT, it's
probably the subject

00:05:15.390 --> 00:05:17.910
that most often
trips up students

00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:20.760
in their PhD qualifying exams.

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:23.450
You know, there's no
better way to strike

00:05:23.450 --> 00:05:27.109
terror in the heart of a
student then to be sitting there

00:05:27.109 --> 00:05:28.650
and ask them a
question while they're

00:05:28.650 --> 00:05:32.480
at the board, what's the
probability that foo happens?

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:34.760
It's like panic sets
in when they've got

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:36.060
to do a probabilistic analysis.

00:05:36.060 --> 00:05:39.330
And now, MIT PhD
students are good.

00:05:39.330 --> 00:05:42.260
You know, they can crank out
the most horrendous calculation,

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:45.880
no problem, come up with really
clever ideas to solve problems.

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:49.170
But you get into probability,
it gets into trouble.

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:51.070
In fact, even the other
faculty sitting there

00:05:51.070 --> 00:05:55.050
start squirming around when
this question's being posed.

00:05:55.050 --> 00:05:57.894
You know, and probability
questions are--

00:05:57.894 --> 00:05:59.810
and we'll see some
examples today-- are always

00:05:59.810 --> 00:06:01.980
the best at faculty
parties, just

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:03.450
can ruin people's whole night.

00:06:03.450 --> 00:06:05.366
You know, what's the
probability this happens?

00:06:05.366 --> 00:06:06.580
And it's some weird answer.

00:06:09.180 --> 00:06:11.130
Now, the strange thing
about this-- well,

00:06:11.130 --> 00:06:13.820
first strange thing is that our
human intuition is terrible.

00:06:13.820 --> 00:06:15.380
And you will see that.

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:17.960
Your intuition will
be wrong, just the way

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:21.840
our brains are
created genetically.

00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:25.880
But the good news is that
probability can be very simple.

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:29.880
If you force yourself to just go
to the basic principles-- which

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:32.920
we're going to cover-- and
go through the basic template

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:35.630
of how to solve a problem--
which we're going to cover--

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:39.370
it is easy, and
you can't go wrong.

00:06:39.370 --> 00:06:43.660
The key is forcing yourself
to just actually write it

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:45.850
down, follow the
basic principles,

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:47.110
and get to the answer.

00:06:47.110 --> 00:06:51.969
As opposed to saying, oh, the
answer's that and here's why.

00:06:51.969 --> 00:06:54.010
Because it's amazing how
often you'll be wrong if

00:06:54.010 --> 00:06:57.620
you just try to rely
on your intuition.

00:06:57.620 --> 00:07:00.730
Now, we're going to start
today our study of probability

00:07:00.730 --> 00:07:04.760
with a famous, simple game.

00:07:04.760 --> 00:07:08.270
And the game is known as
the Monty Hall problem.

00:07:08.270 --> 00:07:11.500
Now, do you all know
who Monty Hall was?

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:12.590
You're probably too young.

00:07:12.590 --> 00:07:14.850
Yeah, OK, not many people
know who Monte Hall was.

00:07:14.850 --> 00:07:19.530
But back in the 1970s, there
was a very popular daytime TV

00:07:19.530 --> 00:07:24.850
show-- a game show--
called Let's Make a Deal.

00:07:24.850 --> 00:07:26.090
And it was a great show.

00:07:26.090 --> 00:07:27.870
It was the precursor
of Wheel of Fortune--

00:07:27.870 --> 00:07:30.240
if you're old enough to
have seen that-- and then

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:31.900
Deal or No Deal after that.

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:34.500
There's always some game
show that's really popular.

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:37.660
Anyway, back in the '70s,
it was Let's Make a Deal,

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:40.132
and Monty Hall was the host.

00:07:40.132 --> 00:07:42.340
How many people have ever
heard of Let's Make a Deal?

00:07:42.340 --> 00:07:44.214
Raise your hand if you've
ever heard of that.

00:07:44.214 --> 00:07:45.630
OK, so it still has some fame.

00:07:45.630 --> 00:07:46.460
Good.

00:07:46.460 --> 00:07:47.690
All right.

00:07:47.690 --> 00:07:50.970
Now, Monty Hall, of
course, was the precursor

00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:54.740
of Pat Sajak of Wheel of
Fortune and Howie Mandel,

00:07:54.740 --> 00:07:56.410
you know, from Deal or No Deal.

00:07:56.410 --> 00:07:59.070
And his assistant
was Carol Merrill.

00:07:59.070 --> 00:08:02.620
She was also famous as
the beautiful assistant.

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:05.430
Now, in Let's Make a
Deal, they TV audience

00:08:05.430 --> 00:08:08.890
would come dressed
up in wild costumes.

00:08:08.890 --> 00:08:12.690
And Monty would go
into the audience

00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:15.240
and pick out a contestant
from the audience based

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:17.620
on how wild their
costume was-- you know,

00:08:17.620 --> 00:08:19.910
somebody that would
look interesting for TV.

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:22.440
And what he would do is he'd
buy a piece of the costume--

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:25.290
maybe their hat or
shirt or something--

00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:27.960
and give them $100 for a
piece of their costume.

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:31.370
And then he would say,
hey look, you know,

00:08:31.370 --> 00:08:34.340
if you give me back the
$100 I just gave you,

00:08:34.340 --> 00:08:37.230
I'm going to let you have
your choice of what's

00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:39.669
behind door number one,
door number two, or door

00:08:39.669 --> 00:08:40.730
number three.

00:08:40.730 --> 00:08:43.320
Or sometimes it would be box
number one, box number two,

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:45.260
and box number three.

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:48.560
Now, because people have
seen the game show before,

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:50.620
they knew that behind
one of the doors

00:08:50.620 --> 00:08:54.380
was a brand new car or
underneath one of the boxes

00:08:54.380 --> 00:08:56.520
was a diamond ring.

00:08:56.520 --> 00:09:00.520
And behind the other doors
were goats or donkeys

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:01.960
or something totally useless.

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:04.010
So one of the three
doors has a big prize,

00:09:04.010 --> 00:09:07.930
the other two got nothing.

00:09:07.930 --> 00:09:11.790
But because anybody would pay
$100 for a one-in-three chance

00:09:11.790 --> 00:09:12.990
at the car, they played.

00:09:12.990 --> 00:09:14.820
And they're on national TV.

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:18.930
So they give the $100 back to
Monty, and they pick a door,

00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:21.830
say door number one.

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:24.690
Monty wouldn't open door
number one right away.

00:09:24.690 --> 00:09:28.110
What he would do is say, OK,
you're sure you like that?

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:29.792
All right.

00:09:29.792 --> 00:09:31.250
Carol, can you
please reveal what's

00:09:31.250 --> 00:09:33.490
behind door number three?

00:09:33.490 --> 00:09:35.270
So Carol opens up
door number three,

00:09:35.270 --> 00:09:37.150
and there's one of the
donkeys sitting there

00:09:37.150 --> 00:09:38.920
or a goat sitting there.

00:09:38.920 --> 00:09:40.650
Well, now there's
only two doors left.

00:09:40.650 --> 00:09:42.500
One of them has the car.

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:46.070
So he'd ask the contestant,
well, you've seen the goat.

00:09:46.070 --> 00:09:48.510
There's a car behind
one of the two doors.

00:09:48.510 --> 00:09:50.620
Do you want to stick
with door number one?

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:54.260
Or do you want to switch
and get door number two?

00:09:54.260 --> 00:09:56.960
And then the audience is
screaming, you know, switch,

00:09:56.960 --> 00:09:59.570
stick, you know, door
number one, door number two.

00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:01.320
You know, the guy's
wife's there screaming

00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:02.840
at him and everything.

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:07.300
You know, he's got to
pick, so he picks one.

00:10:07.300 --> 00:10:12.620
And you know, if he picks the
car, well, his wife's thrilled.

00:10:12.620 --> 00:10:13.760
They live happily ever.

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:15.559
He's a hero on national TV.

00:10:15.559 --> 00:10:18.100
And if he picks the goat, you
know, he's looking at a divorce

00:10:18.100 --> 00:10:20.560
and his career's ruined.

00:10:20.560 --> 00:10:24.250
So it's pretty important that
he gets the right strategy here.

00:10:24.250 --> 00:10:27.380
Now, the question we're
going to look at today

00:10:27.380 --> 00:10:29.670
is whether or not
the contestant should

00:10:29.670 --> 00:10:33.050
switch, playing this game.

00:10:33.050 --> 00:10:35.720
Now, before we do
the analysis, we're

00:10:35.720 --> 00:10:38.540
going to actually play
the game in class.

00:10:38.540 --> 00:10:41.414
I've got three boxes here.

00:10:41.414 --> 00:10:43.330
The game we're going to
play is the same idea.

00:10:43.330 --> 00:10:45.300
The prizes are a
little different.

00:10:45.300 --> 00:10:47.470
Instead of a diamond
ring or a brand new car,

00:10:47.470 --> 00:10:51.700
we've got $10 Toski's
gift certificates.

00:10:51.700 --> 00:10:55.370
You know, your tuition
only goes so far here.

00:10:55.370 --> 00:10:56.790
Instead of donkeys
or goats, we've

00:10:56.790 --> 00:10:59.871
got something much better, the
ever-popular nerd pride pocket

00:10:59.871 --> 00:11:00.370
protector.

00:11:03.470 --> 00:11:06.230
And just to be
clear, this is not

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:08.590
the prize, the gift
certificate here--

00:11:08.590 --> 00:11:10.559
this is much, much better.

00:11:10.559 --> 00:11:11.350
[AUDIENCE LAUGHTER]

00:11:11.350 --> 00:11:15.890
Now, in terms of Monty
Hall, we don't have him,

00:11:15.890 --> 00:11:17.680
but you have me.

00:11:17.680 --> 00:11:20.580
But I am very happy to report
that we're bringing Carol

00:11:20.580 --> 00:11:22.530
Merrill out of retirement.

00:11:22.530 --> 00:11:25.630
She's coming and making a
special appearance today,

00:11:25.630 --> 00:11:28.680
I hope, at 6042.

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:30.882
Do we have Carol?

00:11:30.882 --> 00:11:31.840
GUEST SPEAKER: Hi, Tom.

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:34.140
PROFESSOR: Oh,
yes, we have Carol.

00:11:34.140 --> 00:11:36.186
That's scary.

00:11:36.186 --> 00:11:37.530
[AUDIENCE LAUGHTER]

00:11:37.530 --> 00:11:38.085
Oh, Jesus.

00:11:41.160 --> 00:11:42.190
OK.

