00:19:16.050 --> 00:19:19.500
This is an old version
of Parade Magazine.

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:22.260
And what I'm going to do is
hand out the series of articles.

00:19:22.260 --> 00:19:26.130
And the TAs are going to
help me hand these out.

00:19:26.130 --> 00:19:28.580
There was three of them with
a lot of write-ins here.

00:19:28.580 --> 00:19:32.724
I'm going to give
you a bundle here.

00:19:32.724 --> 00:19:34.859
There you go.

00:19:34.859 --> 00:19:35.400
There you go.

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:36.707
I'll give the rest to Oscar.

00:19:39.960 --> 00:19:40.460
Great.

00:19:54.100 --> 00:19:59.030
Now, Marilyn has a column
every week in Parade.

00:19:59.030 --> 00:20:01.200
And people write in
questions, usually

00:20:01.200 --> 00:20:04.700
about their love life
and weird things.

00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:06.350
And she answers them.

00:20:06.350 --> 00:20:08.210
And she's well
qualified to do this

00:20:08.210 --> 00:20:10.890
because she's listed in the
Guinness Book of World Records

00:20:10.890 --> 00:20:16.350
as having the highest IQ of
a human being ever, at 228.

00:20:16.350 --> 00:20:18.100
And so, you know
she's in some sense

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:21.600
qualified to answer any
question that is written in.

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:26.390
Now, in September of 1990-- and
we're passing out the articles

00:20:26.390 --> 00:20:32.880
now and it shows
the first article--

00:20:32.880 --> 00:20:36.700
this guy named Craig
Whitaker writes in and asks

00:20:36.700 --> 00:20:40.469
Marilyn if you should
switch in this game.

00:20:40.469 --> 00:20:41.510
So you can all read that.

00:20:41.510 --> 00:20:43.830
It says, suppose you're on
a game show and you're given

00:20:43.830 --> 00:20:45.500
the choice of three doors.

00:20:45.500 --> 00:20:47.120
Behind one door is a car.

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:49.180
Behind the others, goats.

00:20:49.180 --> 00:20:52.470
You pick a door, say
number one, and the host,

00:20:52.470 --> 00:20:54.120
who knows what's
behind the doors,

00:20:54.120 --> 00:20:58.910
opens another one, say door
three, which has a goat.

00:20:58.910 --> 00:21:02.480
He says to you, do you want
to pick door number two?

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:05.055
Is it to your
advantage to switch?

00:21:07.720 --> 00:21:10.670
Now, Marilyn writes back
saying, very plainly,

00:21:10.670 --> 00:21:12.070
yes, you should switch.

00:21:12.070 --> 00:21:14.880
The first door had a
one-in-three chance of winning.

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:18.530
The second door has a
two-in-three chance.

00:21:18.530 --> 00:21:21.320
Here's a good way to
visualize what's going on.

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:24.540
Suppose there are
a million doors.

00:21:24.540 --> 00:21:26.780
You pick door number one.

00:21:26.780 --> 00:21:29.480
Then the host, who knows
what's behind the doors,

00:21:29.480 --> 00:21:36.710
reveals every other door
but one and 777,777.

00:21:36.710 --> 00:21:39.900
Well, it would sort
of look like 777,777

00:21:39.900 --> 00:21:43.205
is the one with the car, and
you'd switch pretty fast.

00:21:43.205 --> 00:21:44.620
All right that's her argument.

00:21:44.620 --> 00:21:47.990
That is not exactly a
proof, OK, that the answer

00:21:47.990 --> 00:21:52.450
is you should switch or
that the probability is 2/3.

00:21:52.450 --> 00:21:53.270
All right?

00:21:53.270 --> 00:21:55.140
Now, because she's
giving another problem

00:21:55.140 --> 00:21:58.070
with a million doors, but you've
got a problem with three doors.

00:21:58.070 --> 00:22:01.530
And as we'll see in recitation
tomorrow, the number of doors

00:22:01.530 --> 00:22:03.980
actually matters in terms
of some strategies here.

00:22:06.540 --> 00:22:09.760
So people weren't
convinced by this.

00:22:09.760 --> 00:22:11.510
And so, if you look
to the next page,

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:12.930
you see people writing in.

00:22:12.930 --> 00:22:15.340
And there's a lot a write-ins.

00:22:15.340 --> 00:22:18.830
The first one's by Robert
Sachs, who's actually--

00:22:18.830 --> 00:22:21.360
I looked him up on
Google, and he's

00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:25.450
on the faculty at
George Mason University.

00:22:25.450 --> 00:22:27.390
I also noticed that
in his history,

00:22:27.390 --> 00:22:29.400
he got his BA from Harvard.

00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:32.130
So that should tell you
something about the quality

00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:34.400
of his response here.

00:22:34.400 --> 00:22:38.330
He says, since you seem to enjoy
coming straight to the point,

00:22:38.330 --> 00:22:39.560
I'll do the same.

00:22:39.560 --> 00:22:40.890
You blew it.

00:22:40.890 --> 00:22:42.170
Let me explain.

00:22:42.170 --> 00:22:44.120
If one door is
shown to be a loser,

00:22:44.120 --> 00:22:47.120
that information
changes the probability

00:22:47.120 --> 00:22:49.940
of either remaining
choice, neither of which

00:22:49.940 --> 00:22:53.210
has any reason to
be more likely.

00:22:53.210 --> 00:22:56.340
And so, the answer is one
half of having the car.

00:22:56.340 --> 00:22:58.830
Then he says, as a
professional mathematician,

00:22:58.830 --> 00:23:00.830
I'm very concerned with
the general public's

00:23:00.830 --> 00:23:02.760
lack of mathematical skills.

00:23:02.760 --> 00:23:04.545
Please help by
confessing your error.

00:23:04.545 --> 00:23:07.090
And in the future,
be more careful.

00:23:07.090 --> 00:23:10.810
Just a little gratuitous
extra statement there.

00:23:10.810 --> 00:23:14.270
Next we've got a PhD from
Florida, Scott Smith, who says,

00:23:14.270 --> 00:23:16.600
you blew it, and
you blew it big.

00:23:16.600 --> 00:23:18.210
Since you seem to
have difficulty

00:23:18.210 --> 00:23:22.350
grasping the basic principles
at work here, I'll explain.

00:23:22.350 --> 00:23:24.440
After the host reveals
a goat, you now

00:23:24.440 --> 00:23:26.890
have a one-in-two
chance of being correct.

00:23:26.890 --> 00:23:29.530
Whether you change
your selection or not,

00:23:29.530 --> 00:23:31.150
the odds are the same.

00:23:31.150 --> 00:23:34.140
There is enough mathematical
illiteracy in this country,

00:23:34.140 --> 00:23:37.560
and we don't need the world's
highest IQ propagating more.

00:23:37.560 --> 00:23:39.199
Shame.

00:23:39.199 --> 00:23:41.240
Well, now, this guy is
right about that one point

00:23:41.240 --> 00:23:44.370
about mathematical
illiteracy in the country.

00:23:44.370 --> 00:23:47.290
The next guy, Barry
Pasternack, you know,

00:23:47.290 --> 00:23:50.360
he lists himself as California
Faculty Association.

00:23:50.360 --> 00:23:55.050
He actually was president of the
California Faculty Association.

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:57.870
He says, your answer to
the question is an error,

00:23:57.870 --> 00:24:01.120
but if it's any constellation,
many of my academic colleagues

00:24:01.120 --> 00:24:04.080
have also been stumped
by this problem.

00:24:04.080 --> 00:24:04.580
OK.

00:24:04.580 --> 00:24:07.360
So next page,
