01:13:57.847 --> 01:13:59.284
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:59.284 --> 01:14:01.200
PROFESSOR: What do you think?

01:14:01.200 --> 01:14:06.268
AUDIENCE: So if I pick B and you
pick C, that means [INAUDIBLE]

01:14:09.220 --> 01:14:12.172
[AUDIENCE CHATTER]

01:14:12.172 --> 01:14:22.012
But if he picks A, then
I get [INAUDIBLE] Yeah,

01:14:22.012 --> 01:14:24.010
I'd still get 4, so--

01:14:24.010 --> 01:14:26.752
PROFESSOR: So if you pick
B, what am I going to do?

01:14:26.752 --> 01:14:28.499
AUDIENCE: Oh, you're
going to pick A.

01:14:28.499 --> 01:14:31.040
PROFESSOR: I'm going to pick A.
Let's see how that works out.

01:14:31.040 --> 01:14:36.850
All right, so B has 1, 5, and 9.

01:14:36.850 --> 01:14:40.685
A is, yeah, 2, 6, and 7.

01:14:46.780 --> 01:14:50.670
OK, so you're going to
lose all three there.

01:14:50.670 --> 01:14:53.320
A wins those.

01:14:53.320 --> 01:14:56.950
A wins-- no, you win.

01:14:56.950 --> 01:15:00.967
B wins there, but A
wins the next couple.

01:15:00.967 --> 01:15:02.341
And then, you win
the last three.

01:15:05.500 --> 01:15:13.090
So A wins, again,
5/9 of the time.

01:15:13.090 --> 01:15:15.880
So how is this possible?

01:15:15.880 --> 01:15:26.040
We've got A beats B,
beats C, beats A. All 5/9.

01:15:26.040 --> 01:15:27.885
How is that possible?

01:15:27.885 --> 01:15:29.250
Did we make a mistake?

01:15:32.440 --> 01:15:35.610
Well, why isn't it possible?

01:15:35.610 --> 01:15:40.050
Whoever said probabilities
were transitive?

01:15:40.050 --> 01:15:40.912
Right?

01:15:40.912 --> 01:15:42.370
I mean, you'd sort
of think there's

01:15:42.370 --> 01:15:44.260
a best of the three die.

01:15:44.260 --> 01:15:46.220
But for any one that
you pick, that he picks,

01:15:46.220 --> 01:15:47.428
I can find one that's better.

01:15:47.428 --> 01:15:49.630
And it goes in a cycle.

01:15:49.630 --> 01:15:50.130
All right?

01:15:50.130 --> 01:15:52.820
So you'd think picking
first, you've got a shot

01:15:52.820 --> 01:15:53.780
to pick the best one.

01:15:53.780 --> 01:15:56.890
But picking second
always wins this game,

01:15:56.890 --> 01:15:59.411
if you pick the right one.

01:15:59.411 --> 01:15:59.910
All right.

01:15:59.910 --> 01:16:02.280
You know, since you did
good and figured that out,

01:16:02.280 --> 01:16:05.850
I'm going to give you a
special opportunity here.

01:16:05.850 --> 01:16:06.350
All right?

01:16:06.350 --> 01:16:11.540
Now, I'm going to
let you go second.

01:16:11.540 --> 01:16:13.030
All right?

01:16:13.030 --> 01:16:15.740
So I'm going to
pick one, and I'm

01:16:15.740 --> 01:16:17.360
going to let you pick after me.

01:16:17.360 --> 01:16:19.480
And then we're going to bet.

01:16:19.480 --> 01:16:22.812
There's going to be
a little twist to it.

01:16:22.812 --> 01:16:24.270
But you want to
pick second, right?

01:16:28.235 --> 01:16:30.485
All right, well, let me tell
you what I'm going to do.

01:16:30.485 --> 01:16:32.030
Just to make it-- I want
to do a different analysis.

01:16:32.030 --> 01:16:34.155
We already did these three,
so what I'm going to do

01:16:34.155 --> 01:16:37.289
is an analysis where
we roll them twice.

01:16:37.289 --> 01:16:38.830
Otherwise, it's the
same basic thing,

01:16:38.830 --> 01:16:41.510
but I want to do an analysis
with more outcomes here.

01:16:41.510 --> 01:16:43.310
We've sort of beat
this one to death.

01:16:43.310 --> 01:16:45.210
So I'm going to go first.

01:16:45.210 --> 01:16:52.860
And let's see, what
do I want to pick?

01:16:52.860 --> 01:16:54.520
Hm.

01:16:54.520 --> 01:16:56.720
Well, what should I pick,
if I'm going to do this?

01:16:56.720 --> 01:17:01.330
I guess I'll pick B, all right?

01:17:01.330 --> 01:17:03.190
So I'm going to pick B here.

01:17:06.940 --> 01:17:07.440
All right.

01:17:07.440 --> 01:17:07.970
How much do you
want to bet here?

01:17:07.970 --> 01:17:09.678
I'm going to let you
win your money back.

01:17:09.678 --> 01:17:11.630
I'll let you bet up to $10.

01:17:11.630 --> 01:17:12.245
Your choice.

01:17:15.179 --> 01:17:16.970
What do you-- what do
you want to bet here?

01:17:16.970 --> 01:17:18.280
We've got to put some
money on the table,

01:17:18.280 --> 01:17:19.488
make it a little interesting.

01:17:22.190 --> 01:17:23.314
Yeah, you pick--

01:17:23.314 --> 01:17:25.230
AUDIENCE: Do you roll a
different die or what?

01:17:25.230 --> 01:17:26.438
PROFESSOR: No, the same ones.

01:17:26.438 --> 01:17:27.680
The die don't change.

01:17:27.680 --> 01:17:31.220
I'm picking B. And I'm going
to roll it a couple times.

01:17:31.220 --> 01:17:32.700
And I'm going to
add up my score.

01:17:32.700 --> 01:17:34.700
And then, you get to pick
whatever die you want.

01:17:34.700 --> 01:17:35.783
I'm going to let you pick.

01:17:35.783 --> 01:17:39.770
I mean, I'm going to let you
pick the one that beats it.

01:17:39.770 --> 01:17:41.620
You roll yours a couple times.

01:17:41.620 --> 01:17:43.310
And now we see which
one has the higher

01:17:43.310 --> 01:17:45.393
sum, who's more likely to win.

01:17:45.393 --> 01:17:47.726
AUDIENCE: So it's the sum
total, like you roll a 9 and 9

01:17:47.726 --> 01:17:48.777
and I roll a 7 and 7.

01:17:48.777 --> 01:17:51.110
PROFESSOR: Yeah, then I'm
going to win, because I get 18

01:17:51.110 --> 01:17:52.090
and you got 14.

01:17:52.090 --> 01:17:54.270
If I roll a 9 and
a 1, I get a 10.

01:17:54.270 --> 01:17:56.884
You roll a 6 and a
7, you beat me at 13.

01:17:56.884 --> 01:17:58.360
All right?

01:17:58.360 --> 01:18:02.490
So which one do
you want to pick?

01:18:02.490 --> 01:18:05.740
You could pick C. But you've got
to put the money on the table

01:18:05.740 --> 01:18:08.739
here, whatever you want to bet.

01:18:08.739 --> 01:18:11.280
You know, I want to give you a
chance to win your money back.

01:18:14.830 --> 01:18:18.032
What's the probability
he's going to lose?

01:18:18.032 --> 01:18:19.514
[LAUGHTER]

01:18:19.514 --> 01:18:20.449
You got a T-Card?

01:18:20.449 --> 01:18:21.490
What've you got in there?

01:18:21.490 --> 01:18:23.512
Ah, I'll take the
[INAUDIBLE] card.

01:18:23.512 --> 01:18:24.985
What's that worth?

01:18:24.985 --> 01:18:27.931
Ah, it's worth a few bucks here.

01:18:27.931 --> 01:18:33.390
All right, so I'm picking
B. Which are you picking?

01:18:37.110 --> 01:18:40.304
I've really got his
head messed up now.

01:18:40.304 --> 01:18:41.720
AUDIENCE: There's
$4 on the table.

01:18:41.720 --> 01:18:43.690
Take that and run.

01:18:43.690 --> 01:18:44.690
PROFESSOR: Yeah, really.

01:18:44.690 --> 01:18:46.570
We already saw-- I'll
give you a hint here.

01:18:46.570 --> 01:18:50.860
A beats B. 5/9 of the time,
A comes up higher than B.

01:18:50.860 --> 01:18:54.030
So if we roll them
twice, your odds

01:18:54.030 --> 01:18:59.420
got even better that
A beats B. All right,

01:18:59.420 --> 01:19:03.850
so Will goes with A. Will,
that was a big mistake.

01:19:03.850 --> 01:19:05.020
All right.

01:19:05.020 --> 01:19:06.020
How can it be a mistake?

01:19:06.020 --> 01:19:09.220
A beats B 5/9 of the time.

01:19:09.220 --> 01:19:12.220
Now what we're going to do
is make the decision tree.

01:19:12.220 --> 01:19:15.351
If we roll B twice,
if we roll A twice.

01:19:15.351 --> 01:19:15.850
All right.

01:19:15.850 --> 01:19:17.530
Let's see what happens.

01:19:17.530 --> 01:19:19.090
This is a nasty
one to write down.

01:19:19.090 --> 01:19:20.840
In fact, you'll start
seeing this when you

01:19:20.840 --> 01:19:22.100
do these tree method things.

01:19:22.100 --> 01:19:23.725
Sometimes the trees
get a little hairy,

01:19:23.725 --> 01:19:27.520
so we've got to sort of
approximate it a little bit.

01:19:27.520 --> 01:19:30.140
So here's B, right?

01:19:30.140 --> 01:19:33.950
I got 1, 5, and 9
for my first roll.

01:19:33.950 --> 01:19:36.430
And then I got 1, 5, and
9 for my second roll.

01:19:42.100 --> 01:19:44.590
And I add these up.

01:19:44.590 --> 01:19:47.990
See, if you read the notes
ahead, sometimes that helps.

01:19:47.990 --> 01:19:49.495
6-- here are my outcomes.

01:19:49.495 --> 01:19:51.120
These are the numbers
I'm going to get.

01:19:54.300 --> 01:19:57.000
These are my nine values.

01:19:57.000 --> 01:20:01.360
Your nine values,
you got 2, 6, and 7.

01:20:01.360 --> 01:20:05.170
Then each 2, 6, and 7 again.

01:20:05.170 --> 01:20:15.165
So we add those up, you got 4,
8, 9, 8, 12, 13, 9, 13, and 14.

01:20:15.165 --> 01:20:17.290
And now, we have
each one of these

01:20:17.290 --> 01:20:19.130
against each one of these.

01:20:19.130 --> 01:20:20.830
Because there's 81 outcomes.

01:20:20.830 --> 01:20:22.230
I got four levels to the tree.

01:20:22.230 --> 01:20:25.370
And rather than draw four
levels of this [INAUDIBLE] tree

01:20:25.370 --> 01:20:27.250
to get 81 outcomes,
you're going to say

01:20:27.250 --> 01:20:30.280
that each one of
these corresponds

01:20:30.280 --> 01:20:34.330
to this tree, all right,
that has nine leaves.

01:20:34.330 --> 01:20:40.205
And now we can just count
up how many times I win.

01:20:40.205 --> 01:20:41.630
Well, 2 got nothing.

01:20:41.630 --> 01:20:44.270
That's a 0.

01:20:44.270 --> 01:20:46.120
Let's see how many times 6 wins.

01:20:46.120 --> 01:20:50.064
One-- one time.

01:20:50.064 --> 01:20:53.210
10-- one, two,
three, four, five.

01:20:55.890 --> 01:20:57.050
All right, we've got that.

01:20:57.050 --> 01:21:01.260
6 wins, we already
decided, once.

01:21:01.260 --> 01:21:06.630
10, we decided already,
wins five times.

01:21:06.630 --> 01:21:09.612
14 wins one, two, three,
four, five, six, seven,

01:21:09.612 --> 01:21:12.290
eight, and ties once.

01:21:12.290 --> 01:21:15.390
Tie-- one.

01:21:15.390 --> 01:21:18.550
10, we already got was five.

01:21:18.550 --> 01:21:23.260
14, we already got,
was eight and a tie.

01:21:23.260 --> 01:21:28.000
And finally, I get
18 wins every time.

01:21:28.000 --> 01:21:28.780
Let's add this up.

01:21:28.780 --> 01:21:36.210
I got 17, 22, 30,
35, 36, 41, 42 times

01:21:36.210 --> 01:21:42.370
plus half the ties out of 81.

01:21:42.370 --> 01:21:44.120
How much money's on
this [INAUDIBLE] card?

01:21:49.224 --> 01:21:50.440
Ah, smart guy.

01:21:53.919 --> 01:21:55.410
How did this happen?

01:21:55.410 --> 01:21:58.550
A is more likely to
beat B, higher than B.

01:21:58.550 --> 01:22:00.160
But you roll them
twice, and it's

01:22:00.160 --> 01:22:03.770
less likely to be
as large on the sum?

01:22:03.770 --> 01:22:05.020
Well, why not?

01:22:05.020 --> 01:22:07.760
It's just our intuition's
all screwed up.

01:22:07.760 --> 01:22:10.160
But the math is straightforward.

01:22:10.160 --> 01:22:12.410
In fact, an amazing
thing happens.

01:22:12.410 --> 01:22:17.710
If you roll them twice,
they reverse completely.

01:22:17.710 --> 01:22:22.590
A is worse than B, is worse
than C, is worse than A

01:22:22.590 --> 01:22:24.150
if you roll them twice.

01:22:24.150 --> 01:22:27.570
If you roll them three times,
something else happens.

01:22:27.570 --> 01:22:29.540
In fact, it was known
for a long time,

01:22:29.540 --> 01:22:31.665
this phenomenon
happens with one roll.

01:22:31.665 --> 01:22:34.070
And when I was making lecture
notes a few years ago,

01:22:34.070 --> 01:22:35.869
I noticed they reverse
with two rolls.

01:22:35.869 --> 01:22:37.660
And then we did a class
project to discover

01:22:37.660 --> 01:22:39.830
what happens with k rolls.

01:22:39.830 --> 01:22:44.034
And it turns out that you can
get every possible combination.

01:22:44.034 --> 01:22:45.450
You know, on some
number of rolls,

01:22:45.450 --> 01:22:50.230
A beats both B and C and B
beats C. Other number of rolls,

01:22:50.230 --> 01:22:53.010
A beats them both and C beats B.

01:22:53.010 --> 01:22:55.600
And then, motivated by
that, some researchers

01:22:55.600 --> 01:22:59.330
out in San Diego showed
that there's arbitrarily

01:22:59.330 --> 01:23:03.600
strange dice, now, not
with just three sides,

01:23:03.600 --> 01:23:05.830
but with more sides.

01:23:05.830 --> 01:23:09.025
Such that, for any tournaments--
remember a tournament

01:23:09.025 --> 01:23:11.410
from graph theory,
where everybody beats,

01:23:11.410 --> 01:23:14.580
you know, between a pair of
players, one player wins.

01:23:14.580 --> 01:23:18.130
You can make the relation
for any tournament

01:23:18.130 --> 01:23:20.110
show up for a
particular set of dice

01:23:20.110 --> 01:23:22.489
by rolling a certain
number of times.

01:23:22.489 --> 01:23:24.280
All right, which is
just really fascinating

01:23:24.280 --> 01:23:25.280
that you can prove that.

01:23:25.280 --> 01:23:27.660
So these dice can
get arbitrarily weird

01:23:27.660 --> 01:23:30.900
in terms of which die is
likely to come up and be

01:23:30.900 --> 01:23:32.989
better than another die.

01:23:32.989 --> 01:23:34.280
All right, that's it for today.

01:23:34.280 --> 01:23:35.430
Let me give you your
money back here.

01:23:35.430 --> 01:23:37.055
And I've got a gift
certificate you can

01:23:37.055 --> 01:23:40.170
have for being a good sport.

01:23:40.170 --> 01:23:40.670
Here you go.

01:23:40.670 --> 01:23:42.160
How much money did I take here?

01:23:42.160 --> 01:23:43.697
AUDIENCE: I think only like $2.

01:23:43.697 --> 01:23:44.280
PROFESSOR: $2?

01:23:44.280 --> 01:23:45.620
All right, there you go.

